A somewhat unusual king's pawn opening. White starts by attacking the classical weak spot f7 by his bishop
2...Nf6 is a very good aggressive response in fact "by the book". It attacks the white centre pawn develops the knight and helps to ready for short castling all in one move!

This is a very bad move that instantly brings the position into black's favour. Unless there is a good reason a knight should much rather occupy a centre square not one on the sideline where it covers far less squares

Again an excellent move by black now putting the weak f2 square under attack. Of course black failed to make the probably best move here namely 3...Nxe4 taking white's unprotected centre pawn. But still good.
A bold and agressive move by white not bad at all doubling the threat at f7.
Black's reply (0-0) is clearly the best move here elegantly avoiding the threat and developing at the same time by the castling.

This sacrifice yields nothing after the correct reply which would have been 5...Rxf7 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 where black takes two pieces (knight and bishop) for a rook and a pawn except material loss for white. However....
black moves the king instead. By this move black loses material (the pawn) and much (most) of their advantage already gained. Yet the positions are roughly equal now
Castling had been stronger here

6....Nd5?? is a very bad move. The knight is unprotected at d5 and threatened by three pieces. Sure the move opens up the line from the black queen to the unprotected white knight at g5 but what if white had replied 7. d4! Now black has TWO pieces threatened and undefended and at the same time the g5 knight is now protected!
Instead white takes the offered knight
and black takes the g5 knight but white has now the better position
Unfortunately for white this move not only loses all that advantage (the best move had been 8. 0-0) but is also a serious blunder that is immediately taken advantage of by black
Now white is in serious trouble.
The best move but with correct play by black the game is won

A good move by white
followed by logical play by black (Bxe3 had been good as well)

g6 or Bxe3 had been better. When a player has a material advantage it is often worth the while to do exchanges

Playing white I considered Qh4 Qg3 and Qh5. Qh4 seemed to keep the defense on Qd4 but would give him an opportunity to develop the knight and prepare a castle. Qh5 forces a pawn advance. I still have the dark square bishop he may not want to castle short. Analysis shows Qd1 (a move I really didn't consider) as the best one. I still think maybe Qg3 may have been better. Would value opinions on Qg3 versus Qd1.

I really wish I would have thought through Qd1. It seemed like a retreat but would have been better than this. My thought was to defend d4 first then move Qg3 to defend the fork. At this point I realize I should have moved to Qg3 earlier.
I underestimated the value of the e5 pawn and decided to leave it unprotected so I could pin the knight. I've been told I undervalue pawns and I am starting to understand this comment.

Down one now but still trying to protect c3. Black now seems pretty well formed while I have not determined how to diffuse the c3 pressure point. I noticed I don't really have a consistent strategy. I started out attacking king side but the knight pin fractured that concept.
Black responds to the pin and now I'm thinking about an exit strategy for my queen. However I also know I have to do something about the black queen.

If he moved e4 I would almost have to exchange queens. I don't know how a queen exchange would play out. However the exchange would double black's center pawns so I thought he would retreat the queen.
Black obliges. However now the reasoning I used for move 8. Qh5+ really showed up as flawed. He can easily castle kingside.

I decided to focus on my strengths. I noticed black has a monopoly on white squares but I have the dark squares. Not really sure what to do with this information but the my dark bishop is important to me.

I wasn't sure about this move because my queen is less mobile but I really wanted to get more control of the center. Analysis indicates this is a mistake. In general I think sometimes I play a bit too aggressive without considering the repercussions.
The black castle seems to seal his defense tight. At this point I'm uncomfortable with my earlier Nd4 move.

Even though I was down one the queen trade seemed to be the best option. But now how to deal with the knight? I would like to get my king out of the middle sometime in the near future but I don't see how when the attacks keep coming. The white bishop seems almost useless.
Trying to activate my white squared bishop.

Those c pawns are really troublesome. Because I realized I was undervaluing my pawns earlier in the game I think I have to defend it. I thought about Bd4 then advance the pawn but moving Bd3 opens up for the castle.

I intended on castling the other way but thought somehow if I put my king behind the pawn it would be ok. I also thought having the rook at d1 would be strong support for the bishops somehow. Once I moved I realized how bad this move was. His rooks are lining and the bishop is attacking that side already. I don't know why I moved my king into that mess.
I can see the pawns are going to cause me problems so I want to try and break them up.

In preference to the older move N-B3 so that he can recapture with the Knight on QB4 and so make a strong point of his K5.

White is now ready to free his game by P-QN4 so Black must invade the White position at once. If however 20... Q-B4 to enter at QB7 White replies 21 P-K4. The text move is a finesse to gain time to bring the Queen to Q4. If White now replies 21 P-QN4 Black plays 21... B-Q3 22 P-N3 Q-K5 and the entry square QB7 is again under control.
Missing his last chance of keeping the black Queen off the white diagonals which he could have achieved by 21 P-K4. Now Black breaks in.
A last effort to keep Black out by 25 QR-B1 would fail owing to the weakness of the Q side after 25... P-QR4.
Defence was better by 26 Q-Q1 so that if 26... P-K4 27 R-K2.
Control of the seventh rank is now worth a pawn.

If 28 R-KB1 Black has 28... QxKP 29 B-B4 (not 29 PxQ??? R-N7 ch 30 K-R1 RxP ch 31 K-N1 R(B7)-N7 mate) RxP 30 BxQ R-N7 ch etc. While if 28 Q-B1 Black has 28... Q-Q4 29 B-B4 Q-B6 and the KBP is still vulnerable.
A most attractive forcing of the rank. If now 31 BxR Black has 31... QxNP ch 32 K-R1 Q-R6 forcing mate.

He is reduced to an utterly negative position. One Rook must stay on the KB file to prevent ...P-KN4. The Bishop must stay on its present diagonal otherwise ...B-K4 ch follows. And what of the remaining Rook? If 41 R/4-B4 Black has 41... B-K4 42 RxP BxB ch 43 KxB QxR 44 RxQ KxR with a won K and P ending. If White tries 41 R-K8 ch Black plays 41.. K-R2 42 R-QB8 Q-K5 and more White pawns fall. So White resigns.
